Fix a real, out-of-bounds-read bug in upstream microtar: raw_to_header()
strcpy()s the raw 100-byte name/linkname fields straight off the wire.
ustar's own on-disk format allows either field to use all 100 bytes with
no trailing NUL (a valid, spec-conformant archive) - strcpy() then keeps
reading past mtar_raw_header_t looking for a NUL that may not be there,
on data this module treats as fully untrusted (pymergetic/metal's own
tar.c hands raw guest/host buffers straight to mtar_read_header()/
mtar_next(), never a trusted local file). No src/-side workaround exists:
raw_to_header() is `static`, called only from inside microtar.c's own
mtar_read_header(). See docs/SOURCETREE.md "Vendoring". Applied by
scripts/setup microtar.

diff --git a/src/microtar.c b/src/microtar.c
index 4b89776..e5d0dc6 100644
--- a/src/microtar.c
+++ b/src/microtar.c
@@ -108,8 +108,15 @@ static int raw_to_header(mtar_header_t *h, const mtar_raw_header_t *rh) {
   sscanf(rh->size, "%o", &h->size);
   sscanf(rh->mtime, "%o", &h->mtime);
   h->type = rh->type;
-  strcpy(h->name, rh->name);
-  strcpy(h->linkname, rh->linkname);
+  /* rh->name/rh->linkname are fixed 100-byte fields that a valid ustar
+   * archive is allowed to fill completely with no trailing NUL - strcpy()
+   * would then read past the end of rh looking for one. memcpy() the fixed
+   * width and force-terminate instead (silently truncating that one
+   * boundary case, never reading out of bounds). */
+  memcpy(h->name, rh->name, sizeof(h->name));
+  h->name[sizeof(h->name) - 1] = '\0';
+  memcpy(h->linkname, rh->linkname, sizeof(h->linkname));
+  h->linkname[sizeof(h->linkname) - 1] = '\0';
 
   return MTAR_ESUCCESS;
 }
